This was my second year running the [Pro Football Hall of Fame Marathon](/blog/pro-football-hall-of-fame-marathon-race-report.html).
Last year I was not thrilled with how the race turned out as I had constant nausea for the last ten miles.
I‚Äôm not still not sure how I got to that point, but I was ready for some redemption.

###In Memory of Todd Werley

I was expecting to run this race with a few friends, one of them being Todd Werley who ran a very similar pace as mine.
I met him earlier this year at [Run for Regis](/blog/run-for-regis-50k-race-report.html).

Todd was an amazingly great guy who made new close friends seemingly at every race he went to.
He ran with multiple running groups and had a particular passion for anything veteran and running related.
He ran for [22 Too Many]( https://www.22toomany.com/), [Wear Blue: To Remember]( http://www.wearblueruntoremember.org/), and [Team RWB](https://www.teamrwb.org/).
He was always planning his next big race and encouraging me to sign up too, because the more the merrier of course!

Sadly one week before the race he unexpectedly passed away.
I am heartbroken by his loss, and made the obvious decision to run in his honor.
This entailed wearing blue to remember, pinning his picture to my singlet, and keeping him in my thoughts as I ran.
The race was an emotional roller coaster for me: it was something larger than just going on a run.
The sheer number of runners who showed up on race day with his picture pinned to their bodies was shocking.
It was clear that he had touched numerous lives and I am so thankful to have known him.

